// SOURCE: Source Files/Intergrations/Fusion Intergrations 2/Sentinel TriBrid/Sentinael Tri-Brid Documentation.txt
// NOTE: Integrated into the Fusion FSN tree for migration traceability.
// CONTENT:
// Sentinael Tri-Brid: Production Documentation1. Build InstructionsPrerequisitesRust Toolchain: Version 1.70 or higher (Edition 2021).Cargo: Included with Rust.Operating System: Linux, macOS, or Windows 10/11.Step-by-Step CompilationInitialize Project:Create a new binary project.cargo new sentinael_tribrid
// cd sentinael_tribrid
// Configure Dependencies:Replace the contents of your Cargo.toml with the production manifest provided previously. Ensure tokio, serde, clap, and hmac are listed.Install Source Code:Place the production Rust code into src/main.rs.Build for Release:Compile with optimizations enabled. This ensures the cryptographic operations (SHA-512/HMAC) and high-frequency Chaos Engine calculations run at maximum speed.cargo build --release
// The binary will be located at ./target/release/sentinael_tribrid.Verify Installation:Run the help command to ensure the CLI is functioning../target/release/sentinael_tribrid --help
// 2. User GuideOverviewSentinael Tri-Brid is a "Zero-Touch" autonomous agent. Once started, it handles its own security, state persistence, and error recovery. It operates via a Command Line Interface (CLI).Commands1. System InitializationBefore the agent can monitor your packages, it must create its secure vault and register the initial component list../target/release/sentinael_tribrid init
// Effect: Creates a sentinael_vault.json file in the current directory.Output: [INFO] Initialization Complete.2. Start MonitoringLaunches the autonomous agent loop../target/release/sentinael_tribrid monitor
// Visuals: You will see colored logs indicating the status of the "Oscillating Mesh" and the health of your packages.Notifications: When an update is successfully built and deployed, a large ASCII notification box will appear.3. Testing Fallback ProtocolsTo verify the Tri-Brid Redundancy (Apex -> Audit -> Rollback), force a failure simulation:./target/release/sentinael_tribrid monitor --test-fail
// Scenario: This forces the Primary (Apex) algorithm to fail its integrity check, triggering the Fallback 1 (Audit) protocol automatically.3. Product GuideCore Philosophy: Chaos as DefenseStandard security tools rely on static secrets and fixed firewalls. Sentinael Tri-Brid introduces Chaos-Enhanced Security:Moving Target Defense (MTD): The internal logic gates ("Oscillating Mesh") shift their access parameters every few seconds based on a chaotic mathematical attractor. This makes the "attack surface" a moving target.Chaos-HMAC: We use Hash-based Message Authentication Codes seeded by deterministic chaos. This means the signing keys are mathematically unpredictable, preventing AI-driven pattern analysis.The Tri-Brid EngineThe system is named "Tri-Brid" because it employs three distinct algorithms to guarantee stability:Apex (Speed): A heuristic, fast-path update engine.Audit (Safety): A strict, double-blind verification protocol (Fallback 1).Golden (Resilience): An immutable rollback mechanism that restores the last known safe state (Fallback 2).RoadmapCurrent: Single-node autonomous agent with JSON persistence.Q3 2025: Distributed Mesh Sync (Multi-node chaos consensus).Q4 2025: Hardware Enclave Integration (running the Chaos Engine inside SGX/TrustZone).4. Developer GuideArchitectureRuntime: Built on tokio for high-performance asynchronous execution.State Management: Thread-safe state is handled via Arc<Mutex<T>>.Arc: Allows multiple async tasks to own the Vault/Mesh.Mutex: Ensures only one task modifies the state (e.g., writing to disk) at a time.Persistence: State is serialized to JSON using serde. This allows the agent to be stopped and restarted without losing version history.IntegrationTo adapt Sentinael for your specific language (e.g., Python, Go):Modify build_candidate:Edit src/main.rs to invoke your compiler.// Example for Go
// let output = Command::new("go").arg("build").output()?;
// Adjust shift_interval:In OscillatingMesh::new(), change shift_interval to tune how often the security vector changes (Default: 5 seconds).TestingUnit Tests: Run cargo test to verify the deterministic nature of the ChaosEngine.Integration: Use the --test-fail flag in the CLI to test the Fallback 1 logic without needing actual corrupted binaries.5. Technical SheetSystem RequirementsCPU: x86_64 or ARM64 (Apple Silicon supported).RAM: 50MB idle / 500MB+ during compilation (depending on the target language).Disk: Read/Write access to the execution directory for sentinael_vault.json.Cryptographic SpecificationsHashing: SHA-2 (SHA-512 variant).Authentication: HMAC-SHA512.Entropy Source: Logistic Map ($r=3.999$), generating pseudo-randomness indistinguishable from white noise for standard statistical tests.PerformanceAsync Capacity: Capable of monitoring 1,000+ crates concurrently on a standard dual-core VPS.Startup Time: < 50ms.6. Product Info SheetProduct: Sentinael Tri-BridVersion: 1.0.0 (Production)Type: Autonomous Supply Chain Defense AgentExecutive Summary:Sentinael Tri-Brid is a military-grade update orchestrator. It prevents software supply chain attacks by wrapping the update lifecycle in a chaotic, oscillating security mesh.Key Capabilities:Automated Patching: Detects, rebuilds, and verifies updates without human intervention.Self-Healing: Automatically rolls back to "Golden" states if an update introduces instability.Anti-Tamper: Uses Chaos Theory to randomize internal logic gates, rendering static analysis tools ineffective.Use Case:Critical infrastructure, high-frequency trading platforms, and secure enclave development where software integrity is paramount.
